Quantitative fits of the XRR interface data at −1.20 V were performed by the distorted crystal model, which is widely used to fit XRR of liquid metal interfaces (details on the fitting process are given in Supplementary Methods 1)3,31,33,34,36,39,40. Within the fit errors, the obtained structural parameters (Tables 1, 2, 3) depend neither on the halide species nor on the presence of Pb in the solution. Especially, the Hg layer spacing and the layer decay parameter, which essentially describe properties of the liquid Hg itself, had in all fits identical values of d = 2.76 Å and σb = 0.48 Å, respectively. These results indicate that at this negative potential the halide anion and the amalgamated Pb species do not influence the Hg-electrolyte interface structure, as already shown in our previous studies of the PbFBr system31.Table 1
